Layouts the same, the aisles arranged the same, the counters the same, pretty much u go to one uve been at all of them.  Same products same protocols same prices. Which id say is the best part. They definitely have great prices. And I can guarantee to find stuff my household needs for just a fraction of what it may cost at other stores. And as far as the quality goes, well, its not too bad. I can't complain. You can really count on having dollar general as the go to store for everyday things. I can rely on the products the store offers and save on money every month. Its probably the smartest thing I ever did. But the one less star unfortunately is due to the layout of all the stores. There isn't much room for everything. It seems as if the shelf space is very limited. So products are crammed into each aisle. Which leaves narrower areas to walk through. < UserId.>
111241374458358690197<//UserId.>
<user_name>Indie Author RJ Palmer<//user_name>< Date>
1528695412564< /Date>
<Rate>3<//Rate>< text>
Welcome to the Dollar General... Where NOTHING costs a dollar (not even the store brand, folks) and I seriously don't understand how they have enough employees to shadow each customer individually to make sure they're not stealing.  That doesn't just take talent, it takes professionalism and masterful skills.  They're more like ninjas in that, I kid you not.  I understand that there are thieves everywhere, but dear Lord there's such a thing as too much vigilance because I was beginning to feel unwelcomed.

I ride a motorycle everywhere I go as my daily and normal transportation and because of this, I have a backpack that goes everywhere with me, as well.  I realize that there are places I'm going to be watched more closely, like everyone else is because there's such a thing as healthy paranoia.  It keeps you sharp and focused.  Then, there's the paranoid stalking that comes part and parcel with those who so firmly believe that everyone is out to get theirs that they'll hire a personal security detail for their wall safe at home.  That's not even talking about at the office, folks.  Fort Knox isn't even that secure, in my opinion.

I really do understand that I ride a motorcycle everywhere, and the backpack is a wild card for theft and loss prevention in stores.  I don't understand why I'm singled out for particular attention from both male and female store employees.  The male employees?  That's easy... Chick on a motorcycle.  They don't even have to see me ride the bike to be interested in chatting about it.  The females are a little trickier, responses range from fascinated curiosity to out and out resentment and cold indifference.  I've been riding my bike as daily transportation for a couple of years now; I pretty well know what to expect.

That didn't account for this quantity of attention, though and I even went so far as to ask if it was getting close to closing time because then, I'd have been able to figure out why I felt eyes boring into my back from the moment I walked into the store until the moment I left.  Not kidding again, friends.  I was so uncomfortable as a matter of fact, that it took me more time to write this review than it took me to make my purchases and get out of there.  I was all too happy to leave, if you'd like an illustration and a little perspective there.  That's not normal me.

In short and in the end, the incredible welcome that didn't exist, the misleading prices, and the really rude stalking of the staff places me in a unique position of having to say that I'd only shop at Dollar General under absolute necessity and nothing else.< /text>

Way better than Subway, it's not even close.

This location is great and if you are in a hurry you can order online, call or fax in your order.

< review>
I am highly disappointed in the lack of customer service at the Calabasas Jersey Mikes. I live in Ventura and my son accidently ordered 2 sandwiches online to be picked up from the store in Calabasas. That is too far to drive to pick up any sandwich no matter how good they are. Once I figured out why the sandwiches were not ready for pick-up at the Ventura Mall I called the store in Calabasas. My first call left me somewhat puzzled. The store manager, I will not reveal his name as of yet, told me sorry, there is nothing he can do. He refused to let me speak with his boss but said that he would call him and have his boss call me back. I received no such call of course. I called back and he said that they are on vacation and will call me after they return.
This seems like an easy fix. Most businesses that I have dealt with probably would have given me store credit or called the Ventura store to have them make me a couple of sandwiches. No big deal. I understand that it was a mistake on my sons part and he has owned it. But I am out $20 and with nothing to eat. In my book this is not great customer service. It's too bad, I loved their sandwiches. I guess its "Mikes Way" or the highway.</review>

< review>
It's a cool experience eating the "snow". Their snow looks flakey almost like cotton candy, but it's cold and melts in your mouth. I've had both the matcha monsta and thai tea snow which were both delicious. The matcha monsta has real red beans and strawberries and the thai tea has boba, both also come with mini mochi. Their presentation could use a bit more work, but other than that, it's a great place to grab ice cream. They also have waffle cones and cold/hot drinks.<//review>

<Resp>None< /Resp>< review>
Wonderful location serving taiwanese shaved ice, boba drinks, bubble waffle ice cream treats, and even new additions like their mini lumpia bites.  The staff is very friendly, and the serving size is wuite ample.  One order of their shaved snows can easily feed two.  In a couple of weeks they will also begin doing a halo halo (Filipino traditional dessert) shaved ice.  The location's interior may seem sparse,  but definitely understandable given this is an local restaurant just starting up.  Give it a try, you won't be disappointed.</review>

< rate>
4</rate>
< text>
Reviewed on 2018-11-12

This is about the third time we've been here.  Teenagers often hangout at this establishment, probably because of the same reason as to why my kids got us to come here.

The place is clean and the staff members are friendly.  The decorations on the walls look like a coloring book and use pastel colors that pleasantly soothe the eyes.

My wife and I ordered the honeydew and black milk tea boba.  We enjoy the smooth texture and the soft boba.

The kids opted the "I want s'mores bubble waffles", which comes with vanilla ice cream, marshmallow fluff, chocolate chips and graham cracker crumbling.

We will definitely come back for more, especially since when you check into Yelp they will give you an upgrade from regular to large. I also appreciate the fact that they respect and acknowledge our U.S. Military service members with a 25% discount during Veterans Day!< /text>

(Translated by Google) The beef burritos I bought very stingly are all thin sauce. Two slices of beef even the coriander is too far away from what I ate at Luweiju. Every bite of beef burritos is solid beef for business. Ordered beef roll pancake, extremely stingy with beef and even cilantro. All you can taste is just the pancake and they charge you almost 10 dollars for that. I would rather go to in-n-out for beef burger next time, they give you a solid beef meat patty for half the price.

<text>Mac & Cheese is not something that I grew up with so I don't have the "comfort food" association that many of my friends have about this particular American dish.  It takes a little extra for me to review something publicly; especially if its not something I would go out of my way for.  I go out of my way for Homeroom.  My co-worker introduced me to Homeroom when she ordered for a company luncheon.  Then through a strange set of events, I met Erin Wade.  Homeroom has become a place I am happy to support.  The food is really damn good.  I'm not vegan but the vegan option is creamy and the noodles hold up really well so when I am trying a little harder to make better choices, I don't feel guilty about ordering a batch of vegan mac.  I've ordered the family dinner option for "neighbor" night (an almost monthly event where a bunch of us neighbor's   check in and chat - now social distance rules apply).  On my single girl nights, I order the Aged White Mac and a salad.  Glass of wine, yummy mac and cheese, and a bit of greens to balance it out (boyfriend happily has leftovers for lunch).  Homeroom is a win win.  Order take out or via one of the food delivery services.  It's a comfort food treat that is well worth it.<//text>< resp>

If you\'re looking for larger portions, any of our "Mac Platters" can be made half-baked and will come with heating instructions. Personal-sized "Heat + Eat Macs" are prepped and ready to pop in the microwave. Comes in Classic, Gilroy Garlic, & Aged White Cheddar varieties. < text>
I love this place because the service is always friendly, the food is very GOOD and comforting and you can make your own additions - meat or veggies or go with Vegan, whatever you want --  to already wonderful flavor combinations.Today I had a REALLY rough day at work and thought I'd stop by for dinner after an appointment. I hadn't been back to Homeroom for a very long time. I ordered a side of Brussel sprouts, which I love. I usually only order sides when I can share with friends, but I thought, "Dang, I can eat this for lunch tomorrow." The hostess was so nice. <Rate>5</Rate>< Review>
After a nice long run. I know it's bad to have a cheat meal immediately afterwards, but I was feeling slightly homesick and craved for some comfort food. For starters we had the spicy cauliflower, I ordered the pizza mac which was a daily special. My partner in crime ordered the jalapeno poppers mac. Perfect balance of spicy and cheesy goodness. The pizza mac stayed true to its name and had that stretchy cheesy bite you look forward to on any pizza. The spicy cauliflower was perfect. The slightly charred edges gave it that nutty and beautiful smokey flavour profile. This place really hit the spot in terms of comfort. The staff were lovely, lively, and absolute sweethearts. Perfect attention to detail and super fast. Honestly I don't even remember having to ask or noticing them fill my water glass. It was like a bottomless cup. I definitely can't wait until my next visit.</Review>

Design your own Mac 'n' cheese dish? Yes, please! Had this on our list of places to visit for a while based on an article hubby had read in the news awhile back. Our meal experience did not disappoint. A wide array of add-in options including, peas, chips, CHEETOS?! and so much more. The outdoor seating area is surrounded by succulents and some other blooming plants. Inside, the wallpaper is macaroni-themed and the design of the interior is definitely unique, fun, and modern including potted plants up high on a shelf. The menu is super cute as well and outlines the restaurant's values. From our greeter to our waiter, we were met with a smile and great service. The jalepeÃ±o mac 'n' cheese dish was a tear-jerker for my husband at times, but, I would agree it was totally worth the flavor. Wow!</Text>

<Rating>5<//Rating><Text>The food is amazing and the options are endless.

The parking: only street parking available
Seating: order seating, indoor seating, and community table seating
What do I order: the vegan option because my poor stomach can't take dairy like it used to.
What does my boyfriend order: the Gilroy and garlic, which we've been told is one of the most requested choices.
The beauty of this restaurant: you can add chicken, sausage, vegetables and/or breadcrumbs to your Mac and cheese, or simply create your own.
The prices: ended up paying nearly $50 for these two dishes and two alcoholic drinks
Worth it: Yes, but only once in a while.

< Review>
The service was phenomenal, the interior is super cute, and the portion sizes for the mac and cheeses are enough for two! I really wanted to like the food, but everything besides the honey butter that came with the biscuit was a bit of a bummer. The regular and strawberry limeade tasted watered down and not sweet. The gilroy mac and cheese was garlicy and way better than the jalapeno popper, but both felt like something was missing. The honey butter that came with the biscuit was again the highlight of the meal. The biscuit itself, while pillowy, warm and delightfully biscuit scented, was also dissapointingly tasteless. Maybe I just ordered the wrong things or it was an off day.< /Review>

<gmapID>0x80857dfc830c9779:0x86db31d9371af332<//gmapID><review>This place has amazing food. We arrived here on a Saturday evening around like 7ish. We had to wait about an hour to 45 mins to get a table. I would say this is the only downside to this place but it is worth the food you get for it. The tables may be a shared community table sometimes. You can specify to the staff if you want outdoor seating or a private table instead. They also had heaters for the outside seating.

Coming to the food, it is too good. We got a Gilroy garlic Mac and cheese with mushroom toppings. Make sure to ask for bread crumbs on it. We took 2 sides, fried peas and house made buttermilk biscuit.  I cannot describe the deliciousness. The Mac and cheese was better than any Mac and cheese I've ever eaten. The buttermilk biscuit with honey is one of a kind. I just loved it.

We ordered their peanut butter pie for desert abd ordered beers to go with our food. This place did not disappoint. It is a must try!

One other thing to note, the neighborhood is known for car break-ins and thefts. It is worth parking a bit far away and walking to the restaurant. We found a paid parking nearby for our car. At least we could eat our food in peace without worrying about our car.< /review>< Time>

<Text>I had their mac & cheese back in like 2009? when they had a stand at the eat real festival in Jack London. It was fantastic, but it was served in a small bowl, the way mac & cheese should be (IMHO) I was super excited for them to open, but when they did, the price was pretty steep so I just didn't bother. I have grabbed take out 3-4 times over the years and it's OK, but not worth the price. (at least in my opinion). I mean, you do get a lot of food, but it's just mac & cheese, and it's only OK. Don't get me wrong, it's way better than boxed stuff, and a lot of people love it. I am not one of them. I will say this, if you need a side dish for a backyard BBQ or a potluck or whatever, their food would really shine. Because as good as mac & cheese is, it's way too rich for a main course. It tastes much MUCH better when it's balanced with a separate, starchless, vegetable and maybe a protein. This is just my opinion, eat what you want. Honestly I haven't been there in a while. If they offer a complete meal (entrÃ©e, with vegetables & mac as sides) , I would give them another shot.</Text><pictures>None< /pictures>< resp>

<user_id>116531973308303483413< /user_id>< user_name>
Brandy< /user_name>
<date>1573864959818< /date><Rating>4<//Rating>< Text>
This place is mac and cheese central. No vegan mac on the menu yet though. Big hearty pasta is used to start. They have several sauce options, like a Gouda based mac, a buffalo, a cheddar a garlic, etc. You can customize your own Mac or choose from the tested and loved premade choices. You can add in veggies like broccoli or shrooms, meats like bacon or chicken, and toppings like crushed potatoes chips or breadcrumbs( and many more add ons) that get baked together in a piping hot dish. One order is enough for 2 to split, or have leftovers to take home. Or it's enough for a super hungry person. They have a few good sides and salads. They also have great dessert options. They are busy all the time and for good reason. Great comfort food! They also have a takeout counter one block over if you don't want to wait. They have outdoor seating with heaters and if you have a group larger than 4 call ahead. Kid friendly, great service.</Text>

<name>Tobiah Talsma</name><time>1549521923846< /time><Rate>4</Rate>< text>
A well-known, local favorite stop for creative variations of the classic Mac n' Cheese. I visited the main restaurant which was busy, and the Chicken Pot Pie Mac n' Cheese was good on a cold January night. Although it wasn't 5-star quality it was good enough to keep me curious and determined to come again and try something else. The service was good, although oddly they seemed rushed to seat the two of us. Normally I enjoy quick service but perhaps because they were eager to wedge us between crowded tables it came off slightly pushy. We eventually were comfortably seated outside under warmers and it was nice! Will definitely be back.< /text>

< Review>
This place has a really fun vibe (evident by the name).  Parking was easy and service was swift.

Cost is a little on the high-side for a mac n' cheese dish (even considering they're gourmet), but it was pretty tasty and doable for an occasional treat.  We had the 'Smoked Cheddar and Bacon', and 'Mexican.' Both we super creamy and cheesy, filled with the appropriate topping, and quite filling.

Their sangria iced coffee weren't bad, either.<//Review>

<review>I had heard a LOT of hype about Homeroom before I actually got to try it, so my expectations were pretty low.  I've also had some transcendent mac n' cheese experiences (Beecher's in Seattle), so the bar is pretty high.  I was very skeptical.

Homeroom exceeded expectations and I reluctantly had to cave in to the hype.  This is legit.  We ordered the classic mac n' cheese with chicken, and the white cheddar mac n' cheese, both with breadcrumbs.  We also got some of the brussels sprouts.  Everything was delicious.  I have to say I think the chicken was superfluous; the mac n' cheese is plenty filling without it, and it really didn't add a whole lot.

Everything was just amazing and delicious and I want to go back.  I can't really say much else.  Oh yeah, good beer.< /review>< userid>

< Text>
If you're ever craving mac n cheese or you just aren't sure what you want and you're in the Oakland area, definitely stop by at Homeroom and get you some mac n cheese! They've got a pretty good selection of options on their menu which provides variety from buffalo chicken, bacon ranch, jalapeÃ±o popper, or if you want something on the "healthier" side, there are options with crab/spicy crab with peppers onions and parsley, and my personal favorite - the macximus, which has artichoke hearts and spinach with shallots feta and Jack cheese. The Macximus is truly one you can't go wrong with, but in reality all of their options seem to have great flavor and even look aesthetically appealing. They've got some adult beverages but if you don't drink they also have some very refreshing limeade's and iced teas, I highly recommend the paradise tea which is essentially a black hibiscus tea, it doesn't halve any sweetener, but you don't even need to add sugar! On a final note. I'd like to take this moment to appreciate their staff for their diligence and efficiency, as well as their great customer service. Besides our server, I noticed every other employee working hard to take care of their customers, from the host getting us seated - which, mind you it was really busy and looked like the wait was at least 30mins but we got seated in about 10 maybe 15mins tops. The service is truly great, the food came out pretty quick, and the entrees are pretty big!  You won't regret going to Homeroom, I guarantee it.</Text>

< user_name>
Josh Buck< /user_name>
<date>1563117493664</date><rating>3< /rating>< Review>
I'm conflicted on what to say here. The food was tasty and the staff friendly, but the customer service was a bit out of wack.

We started by ordering for the kids as we didn't want a meltdown in the restaurant by hangry children. This caused a bit of confusion as they have to put the whole table in at once. The server had to ask the cooks if they could accommodate this request...really? But they could and all was ok.

We ordered the classic Mac and cheese for the kids...one bite and they pushed it away and refused to eat it. The issue wasn't that it was bad, but they didn't like the flavor. We called the server over and explained the situation and asked to replace it with another meal. The server explained that since we ordered it there was nothing he could do, but he'd be happy to get something else for the kids. And for our inconvenience, he would give us a free dessert. Again, really? What restaurant doesn't return a dish if you don't like it (again, literally one bite was removed). It's like like we ate 1/2 the dish then tried to argue we wanted our money back. And we ended up ordering a replacement dish that was 2x as expensive.

Then they had to check again to see if they could make a regular dish in a kids size...no. not a big deal, but not sure why that was a problem. And we ordered one dish without breadcrumbs, and it still came with them..again, no big deal, but it was one more thing.

So in the end we ordered a dessert that was almost as expensive as the kids meal. If they had just refunded us the money for the kids meal, we still would have spent a lot more, and the evening wouldn't have been tainted.<//Review>

<UserId.>106196871769362082373< /UserId.>< username>
Thomas G< /username>
<Time>1520523989740<//Time>< rating>
5</rating>
< Text>
Life changing comfort food. I came here on a Sunday with a line out the door. I waited 5 minutes and passed the time looking at an English Bulldog sleeping beneath a table. Always nice to know a place is dog friendly. We got in quick because we told them we were fine sitting anywhere, so they put us at the "counter". Scare quotes around this because it's not a proper counter, more the flat surface atop a divider separating the dining room from the register and work area. There was no leg room so if you're tall, don't sit here.

I got the buffalo chicken Mac and front the first bite I knew I couldn't tell my dad that I'd been here and discovered a Mac n Cheese better than his. It was rich and creamy with just the right amount of cayenne kick and tang from the Frank's Redhot they use. The chicken was perfect and I don't say that lightly. American chicken is almost universally overcooked but the tiny cubes in my dish were tender and m**st. It came with breadcrumbs on top and a tasteful amount of ranch. I took the second half home and ate it for dinner making homeroom account for 2/3 of my meals that day.

I told others that I had finally been to Homeroom and they acted like I had just entered the real world. I was now party of the people in the know. Join the club.</Text>

<user_name>Mike Lawson</user_name>< Review>
Delish!

I had the original, my date had the spicy.  So. Good.

The ambiance was cool (check out the photos in the bathroom).  Parking was easy.  Prices were okay (a bit on the high side).  This place only serves Mac & Cheese...so the wait time is quick because the macaroni is always prepared and waiting for you.

Totally hipster, but fun.</Review>

<userid>110017591137562417452</userid><Name>Edward Elliott<//Name>< date>
1434038277043< /date>
< Rate>
1</Rate>
< Text>
Showed up at 9:35 PM, 25 minutes prior to their posted close time of 10 PM... After waiting at the host stand for 5 minutes,  we were informed that they stopped seating at 9:30 PM. I sited the 10 PM advertised close time,  and I didn't say it,  but in my 45 years I've never experienced a restaurant that wouldn't seat to a reasonable time before close.  The restaurant was 75% full and clearly going to have guests well beyond 10 PM. The host kindly said he'd ask the manager if they could make an exception.   This was kindly appreciated given our first visit to this abode; unfortunately, the manager recited their policy. I said,  "Yeah,  we were five minutes  late then,  but it's our first time here.  Any chance... ?"  No luck!  I suggest they change their closing time to 9:30 PM, and honor seating like every other restaurant until their posted time of closing.  Their convenience is obviously more important than the customer!   I figure I'll never try their food now,  given this poor service experience.   What if I'd have been a food critic wearing my "press badge"?  That would have likely illicited the kitchen staying open till midnight.  I just think (within reason) that businesses should try to meet their customers!  Oh, though I've never tried it,  I'm sure that the removal of the 'truffle mac' was more for the savings of the business,  than the upset fan base that were told it was removed to 'save you - the customer's - money'.  That point rang in my mind (see their website) as we were casually turned away!< /Text>

<text>I love the variety of mac & cheese here! On my first visit, I ordered the classic with bread crumbs and added broccoli which is my go to. The creaminess was well balanced and the amount of broccoli was well placed all over. The amount of mac & cheese you get in a plate is very fulfilling that it's reasonable for the price. I have a reasonable appetite so I can only finish half of a plate and save the rest for my lunch the next day. If you have a hefty appetite, you can probably finish the whole plate. The service can be a little slow at times, but the staff are really friendly. One disappointing thing is that their sides should expand a little. <date>1523896869448< /date><UserId.>114774920147643950426< /UserId.><user_name>Sunkwan Chang< /user_name><pictures>None</pictures><GmapID>0x80857dfc830c9779:0x86db31d9371af332< /GmapID><Review>(4.5 stars if I could)

Delicious Mac'N Cheese! With all the hype, I was a little disappointed as it was not the "life changing Mac and cheese" I came to hear of, but I was quite pleased at the end of the day. Not as soft as I expected it, but a bit chewy. Nice and flavorful with a breadcrumb topping option. Huge portion sizes, especially considering it is Mac and Cheese - be ready to take some home.

For price, you get great bang for your buck. High quality food and a lot of it, for a not super high price. Expect to spend ~$13. Definitely add in meat or veggies, ask your server for recommendations. The food kind of needs it; even hardcore cheese lovers will have a hard time with all that fatty cheesy goodness.

Nice atmosphere and pleasant staff. I was late meeting a friend and was in a bit of a rush, but the staff were relatively understanding and courteous. Atmosphere is great, relaxed place for a conversation. Possibly a good date spot. Wish I took a picture, it was quite nice.

Not life-changing-ly brilliant, but an excellent spot for dinner with friends, family, or a casual date. Definitely unusual and will definitely be coming back. 4.5 stars if I could.<//Review><Rate>5<//Rate></record>

< user_name>
Samuel Shaw<//user_name>
<Rate>5< /Rate><Review>Call ahead or get there early, because this place gets packed! It's worth the wait: Homeroom offers heaping portions of mac 'n cheese with a variety of combinations. Get ready to customize your choice in cheese, topping, and mix-ins.

Most tables are shared; you'll be sitting with fellow cheese fans in a loud, boisterous  room; or, outside at one of several tables. Despite the crowd, our food arrived within 10 minutes, and it was delicious. Brussels sprouts were fantastic on the side, and the bacon baked into mine was crunchy and cooked to perfection.

The wait staff brought to-go boxes unprompted when they saw we had slowed down. Great service, good price, and great choices - we'll be back!</Review><UserId.>117834273765218431100< /UserId.>< Pictures>

< text>
In general, delicious Mac n cheese.  I think the consistency and quality of their food could be improved, but overall good enough that I'll be coming back. This time around, the Mac I ordered came to my table luke warm, but the staff were kind enough to heat the food up again for me.  The sauce was delicate and cheesy, but the texture of the noodles was a bit plasticky, with not much bounce back on the chew.  The one glowing point is that homeroom offers GF Mac which is delicious, and admittedly more to my liking (at least this visit). If you eat GF, praise the pasta gods, because homeroom has answered your prayers. ðŸ˜Š</text>

I was told to go here by one of my clients, Juan (works in to go). He said he worked there and always made sure the food is amazing. So I took his advice and went there. I'm glad i did because I was blown away by the quality of the food and the pricing. The wait time wasn't bad at all, their ipa selection is good, and the food was nothing short of incredible! I found it hard to finish my full meal though, I ended taking it home and their homemade Oreo cookie. I tried to give my compliments to Juan but I ended saying Juampi (I confirmed I said the wrong name to the staff with the others I went with, I blame the IPA's lol). If you'd like to take someone on a date, have a cheat day, or just enjoy a good meal and a drink you can't go wrong with homeroom. Also I think our servers name was Kevin, he was a good guy too! Thanks again Juan!  I've been recommending this place to everyone who asks "what's good to eat in Oakland?"<//review>

<gmap_id>0x80857dfc830c9779:0x86db31d9371af332< /gmap_id>< text>
The primary focus is macaroni and cheese, which is perfectly executed in a variety of ways and even available gluten-free. Everything is fresh and homemade, down to the salad dressings.

I tried the staff pick, which was a baked potato mac with the (optional) green chiles - very tasty, well balanced, and filling.

Service is attentive, the decor is cute / kitschy (tables made of former bleachers), and the neighborhood is 'up and coming' but I did not feel unsafe.

We did not try the desserts (too full!), and while they have blue bottle coffee, the only iced tea is icky tropical fruit flavored Paradise Tea.</text>

< Text>
Ok. Get ready to drop some cash on mac and cheese. First and foremost. If you're one person, you're good. If a family, yeah, you're dropping some cash on mac and cheese. Beyond that... the mac and cheese is delicious and varied, it's like a pizza shop with the toppings and extras you can add. The tap is good too, and the beer pairings actually make sense. Oh, and the brussels sprouts are a problem. Ensure you come hungry, and plan ahead to be taking a doggy bag home (or don't but, you will be stuffed, for sure). When the mac and cheese is the meal, you know its going to be a party. Enjoyed thoroughly.</Text>

< review>
First time I went, the place was absolutely 5stars, in everything. This more recent visit in may 2018 (one year later) it was 5 stars for service, the waitress gave honest and helpful suggestions, 5 stars for drinks, but only 3.5 or 4 for the food, because while the flavor and spice was excellent my pasta was too al dente for my tastes. My friend tried mine too and agreed - not quite done! The pasta in her dish, on the other hand, was spot on. So I was a little disappointed, to be honest.
I definitely recommend getting the bread crumbs on top, and peas. And arrive early if you dont want a long wait!<//review>

<userid>117298439357852062985<//userid><user_name>Simon Waddington< /user_name><Time>1512544723264</Time><rate>4<//rate><review>If you can avoid the wait it is a great place to go for really tasty Mac-n-cheese that most people make nowhere near as tasty. Their menu these days has a huge variety of options beyond the basic.

My most recent selection was the Sriracha version with peas and bacon added, very tasty, would have been even better with one of their beers. They even have a pizza Mac now, apparently pretty good too.

I don't think I've ever eaten dessert there as I'm always too full, but it looks like there are some good options. You can also go to their to-go location a block away and avoid the wait. .

In the vicinity a bunch of new and interesting stores have sprung up - a record store, bike store, guitar store and coffee shop. Definitely hipster friendly!</review>< Pictures>

<Time>1507591084383< /Time><text>I never kind paying a little more money for this mac & cheese than I normally would. It's definitely not an Oakland secret anymore, so going anytime on a weekend or around typical "dinner" hours on a weeknight might find you waiting a little bit. But if the weather is good, it's totally worth it. I love going to lunch to grab a mini mac and salad combo (the citrus vinaigrette is to die for!!), but I am happy no matter what time I dine. I oscillate between the Vermont White Cheddar and the Gilroy Garlic, but you can't really go wrong with any of the macs. For dessert, you have to do the oreo cookie at least once! Bonus points for the times I bring my dog and dine outside: they always bring a bowl of water and give her a few biscuits!< /text>< pictures>

< text>
Homeroom is a very cute mac and cheese restaurant decorated like a classroom. There's a library card catalog, a chalkboard wall, and paper airplanes hanging from the ceiling. They have a wide variety of mac 'n cheese with different kinds of cheese and toppings and none I've ever tried have been a miss. <Response>None<//Response>< Text>
Overall my experience here has been generally poor. Lines going out the door meant we were seated in around half an hour. Once we ordered service was decent, but nothing special. Food for me was not good. My mac and cheese tasted decent, but no better than an Annie's mac and cheese box. Also I ordered a brownie for dessert. The Brownie had way too much baking soda in it. It tasted more salty than sweet and had me coughing. Besides the restaurant being nothing to write home about, my home is near Homeroom. It has definitely made the neighborhood a bit more annoying to live in. Remember those lines out the door. Imagine trying to walk through those huge crowds, especially if you have to catch a BART or something. People cross the street illegally and trample plants just to get to Homeroon. In short, I reccomend not coming here alot, as food is only decent but costs way too much, and it makes the neighborhood worse. Thank you for your time.<//Text>

Definitely a conveyer belt of mac'n'cheese. Happy they have gluten free options, but I wouldn't go out of my way to return.
They have creative selections and interesting ingredients.< /review>

<UserId.>106226941420364887072< /UserId.><user_name>Alyx Barranger< /user_name><Time>1384890206861</Time>< Rate>
2<//Rate>
< Text>
I really struggled with Homeroom when I was deciding how to review them.  The fact that I, the lover of everything Mac 'n cheese, did not instantly fall in love with this place upon my first bite was my initial concern.  All of my friends were raving about how I of all people *needed* to try Homeroom.

Unfortunately, the food was just mediocre.  After spending 4 years in St. Louis, my standard for noodles comes from Noodles & Co.  If you are not a chain restaurant, I expect you to provide better food than Noodles could.  Homeroom just didn't do that.  I got the truffle mac n cheese and the garlic one and both were surprisingly bland even though those flavors should have been knock outs.  Also, the pasta shells were undercooked.

All in all, it was a very disappointing experience.  I only come to Oakland a couple of times a year, so I doubt that I will return.< /Text>

<username>Uriah Sayres< /username><time>1352881490783<//time>< Rating>
3</Rating>
<Text>As a recent transplant to the Bay, I made it my imperative to try the places people seem to rave about. Homeroom is good, albeit variable.

One day I went and decided upon the Gilroy Garlic. It was described as having the perfect amount of garlic, which at most places is far too little. I got it and it ended up being super garlicky and delicious. Thumbs up. The next time I got the Gilroy Garlic, I seriously couldn't taste the garlic. That sort of variation is okay if the dish isn't premised on being garlicky. I've also noticed variation in how much of the additives you get. If I'm gonna pay 2 dollars for caramelized onions, I feel like it should have more than one strand every few bites.

At the end of the day, I'll go again, but this local hotspot is good, not great. All they need is a little more focus in the kitchen and this place will be an even bigger hit.<//Text><pictures>None</pictures>< resp>
None</resp>

<user>105005710423946377208<//user><username>Tyson Roberts< /username>< date>
1342453044587<//date>
<Rating>4</Rating>< Text>
You don't have to tell me twice - a place with actual "good" Mac & Cheese, as opposed to the kind you got in the cafeteria as a kid?  Sign me up!

My compatriot really wanted to take me there, but wanted me to temper my expectations (she was terrified I'd be let down).  As it turns out, she had nothing to worry about.

Down to the food:
Vermont White Cheddar (with breadcrumbs): Awesome.
Gilroy Garlic Mac (with peppers and breadcrumbs): Heavenly
Homemade root beer: quite good - I loved the raw sarsaparilla taste, and the fact that it was light and not overly sugary.

Ended up eating 1.25 dishes (couldn't let my compatriots' food go to waste!)

No room for dessert.</Text>

<userid>116796911158844589160<//userid><username>Noelle Ham<//username>< date>
1399577539433<//date>
<Rating>3<//Rating><text>I tried a sample of the gilroy mac at Oakland's Eat Real Festival. It was just a simple bowl of mac and cheese, so I was apprehensive on how good it could really be. But boy was I wrong. The flavors exploding in your mouth, the noodles were cooked perfectly. I fell in love (and I don't even really like mac and cheese!)

When I finally got a chance to hit up homeroom, I was excited! My party of 3 showed up around 5:30 and only had
to wait about 5 min before we were seated. So many options! I ended up deciding with the exchange student, while the other two in my group got the smokey bacon and crab. Oh, and breadcrumbs on all of them!

We started off with the Brussels sprout appetizer. Delish!! These morsels are crispy and oh, so tasty. They were actually a favorite of the night!

When we finally got our orders, we dug in. The portions are quite large (I mean, you can only eat so much before you'll explode). I loved the flavors of mine. That ginger butter!! So subtle, but then bursts in your mouth with the sriacha kick. I tried a bite of my friend's crab mac and it was packed with crab!

While the flavors were yummy, the gripe I have was that the noodles were under cooked. They still had that "raw" taste and were a bit crunchy. It was to the point where it was just raw noodles, but after awhile it left a blahh consistency and taste in your mouth.

We ended our meal with the grasshopper pie which was delicious! I only had a bite, but it's surprisingly light!

By the time we left, there was a huge waiting list out the door. So I suggest trying to come early or an off time.

I'm willing to try it out again eventually and hopefully have a better bowl of mac! It could have just been an off night.<//text>< pictures>
None</pictures>

< Text>
Casual nice place in Oakland serving mainly macaroni and cheese. They have many varieties. The spicy mac & sriracha macs are good & spicy. The garlic mac is also good - add breadcrumbs to that. In the past, have had Vermont White Cheddar & the 4 cheese mac which were very good - not an overwhelming cheese flavor but cheesy, Gilroy Mac which was also good with the garlic was not too strong, & Jalapeno Popper Mac which was off the menu, but very good, not truly spicy but has a slight tinge that is just right. The Ivy leaguer, Spring Mac & Popper Mac were also very good. We also had their side of minty peas which was nice. Spicy cauliflower was ok - I would not get that again. The macs are quite filling, so one is good for 2 people. The grilled cheese with jalapeno jam was good, but sweet so you may or may not like it. The peanut butter pie is unique & good. We also liked their brownies & grasshopper pie. They have their homemade drinks like limeade, key lime pie, & rootbeer. The service is good. Lunch is a good time to go, but in the evening, the space gets tight, it is lively & louder. Parking is on the street.<//Text>

<Date>1544326925600< /Date>< Rate>

<text>Watery cocktail, oversalted macaroni. Never again<//text><pics>None<//pics><Resp>None</Resp>< gmapID>
0x80857dfc830c9779:0x86db31d9371af332<//gmapID>
</record></dataset><record>
<Pics>None<//Pics>< text>
This isn't your every day Mac and Cheese from a box, Homeroom serves up the old school children's classic with a gourmet twist and it's worth a visit (multiple visits even!)

I don't usually ever think of mac and cheese as an entree in restaurants. Most often it's just a side and maybe if you added some sort of fancy meat, then you could call it an entree. But at homeroom, mac and cheese is the star and about the only think you can get here besides dessert and drinks. I came here with my sister on a Saturday evening and it was packed. We came a little bit earlier than the dinner rush so we didn't have to wait too long for a table. We decided to get the Gilroy Garlic with broccoli, caramelized onions, and the bread crumbs and the Mexican mac and cheese with bread crumbs on top as well. I also ordered an arnold palmer and banana cream pie for dessert.

The Gilroy Garlic was simply delicious. I thought the mexican mac and cheese was good. The hint of chipotle in there and the chorizo really made it unique but it had nothing on the gilroy garlic. I am a huge fan of garlic so this mac and cheese just won my heart. The garlic was strong but really went well with cheese. It was just delicious, cheesy, creamy, and rich. I also really liked the caramelized onions in it as well because it added a hint of savory sweetness. I REALLY like their macaroni, it's firm but chewy. They're also pretty big which I like over tiny small macaroni. One order is enough for one person and maybe even two if you're not really big eaters. My sister and I had a lot left over. I loved the breadcrumbs on top of both mac and cheese, added a nice crunch. I was glad that I ordered the arnold palmer because the sourness of the drink really cut the richness of the mac and cheese which helped me eat more otherwise the richness of the cheese was really too much. The banana cream pie came in a cute jar topped with caramel. I loved the banana chunks but it was a little too sweet overall for my liking.

The servers here were really friendly and I really liked the vibe of the restaurant. It was really open and modern. It's an awesome place to eat and drink with friends. Their drink menu wasn't large but it was interesting, they had some fun boozy creations. If you're ever craving mac and cheese then treat yourself out to something better than that kraft's box and check out Homeroom.< /text>

1423200484225< /Time>

<Time>1422322981683<//Time><Text>For my 100th review, I couldn't think of a better place to review. Homeroom specializes in my absolute favorite thing to eat and it truly earns a 5 star rating in my book.

I've been here twice now and it has yet to disappoint me. The wait can be long at times, but just grab a drink at the bar while you wait. Sitting at the bar allows you to be out of the cold and to catch glimpses of the cooks make delicious mac and cheese in the kitchen.

My favorite thus far is the Gilroy Mac w/ bacon and buttery breadcrumbs. Delicious is not even a good enough word to describe it. The portions are huge and it's enough for 2 meals. Most of the time I can't stop myself from eating most of it and later regret my decisions when the food coma hits.

I've also had the Dungeness Crab Mac and Ivy Leaguer: Truffle Mac and didn't really enjoy them as much as I enjoyed the Gilroy Mac. I don't suggest getting the Ivy Leaguer just because the thyme is really overpowering and you can barely taste the truffle. The dungeness crab mac is good, but a little too pricey for the amount of crab they add.

My love for mac and cheese is embodied in this restaurant and I'll be back to try the rest of the mac and cheeses offered. I only wish they opened a location in LA or even SF.< /Text><Rating>5<//Rating><gmapID>0x80857dfc830c9779:0x86db31d9371af332< /gmapID>< pics>
